# Branch per Task

Referenced from `AGENTS.md`. Every new unit of coding work starts on a new branch — never commit feature work directly on `main`.

## When to create a branch

Create a branch **before the first code change** when:

- The user gives a new implementation task (feature, fix, refactor, UI change).
- The task is a distinct unit of work, even if it continues the same feature area.

Skip branching when:

- The session is read-only (questions, reviews, planning only).
- You are already on a branch created for this same task in the current session.
- The user explicitly says to stay on the current branch or work on `main`.

## Branch workflow

```bash
git status
git branch --show-current
```

If starting a new task and currently on `main` (or a branch for a different task):

```bash
git checkout main
git checkout -b <type>/<short-description>
```

| Prefix | Use for |
|--------|---------|
| `feat/` | New feature or UI |
| `fix/` | Bug fix |
| `refactor/` | Structural change |
| `chore/` | Tooling, docs, config |